#{\footnote PG_OVERVIEW}
${\footnote Overview}
+{\footnote BW_PG_1}
{\b\f0{\cf2\scaps Programmer's Guide}\line\fs32 Overview}\par\pard\sb100

The MythOS\'99 collection provides programmers of
 entertainment/multi-media software with a wide array of useful
 tools which can be used in relative isolation or combined with
 other components to form a base technology for engine
 development.
\par

This collection of tools is designed for use with Microsoft
 Visual C/C++ v6.x and the Windows 95/98/NT environment.  The libraries
 were developed using Microsoft Visual C/C++ version 6.0 and
 Microsoft's MASM Assembler version 6.14. Microsoft's Program
 Maintenance Utility Version 1.20 was used for the makefiles.  Some
 of the components may require the DirectX SDK V6.1 and the DirectX
 Media V6 SDK.
\par

Because of the nature of the Windows environment, a number of
 application-side initialization steps are required.  Therefore,
 the Win32 version of MythOS includes an application framework
 called {\i SimGine}  This framework includes all needed
 initialization code and demonstrates the intended use of the
 library components.  Example code in the MythOS distribution
 demonstrates both the use of {\i SimGine} and direct initialization
 of the MythOS components.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Audience}\par

This guide is intended for use by programmers who have a working
 understanding of C and C++ programming, Windows 32-bit
 programming and the Win32 API, and some x86 Assembly.  Certain
 libraries may assume more specialized knowledge.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Features}\par

The major features of the MythOS collection are:
\par

High-performance, high-quality 2D and 3D graphics engine, including font
 support.
\par

Supports high-resolution 8- and 15/16-bit devices using Windows WinG DIB,
 DirectDraw\'ae, and Direct3D\'ae as well as selected proprietary 3D APIs for
 direct 3D hardware support.
\par

Provides support for Gouraud-shaded, perspectively texture-mapped output,
 including specular effects at real-time speeds.
\par

Supports hierarchical polygonal models, as well as specialized draw entities
 for sprites, polygonal terrain, particle systems, and others.
\par

Easily extendible design.
\par

Custom memory-management functions for high-performance malloc-style, arena,
 and handle-based memory allocation.
\par

Non-preemptive, multi-threaded, real-time kernel.
\par

Abstract event processing system, including support for keyboard, mouse, and
 joysticks using the Win32 or DirectInput\'ae interfaces.
\par

Precision timer services.
\par

File system for quick development of data control and processing routines
 including support for IFF and a variety of bitmap formats.
\par

Network interface wrapper for DirectPlay\'ae.
\par

Sound library wrapper for DirectSound\'ae including support for various
 sample file formats and direct-from-disk file streaming.
\par

Animation/movie player library including support for
 ActiveMovie/DirectShow\'ae.
\par

A Newtonian-physics simulation system for velocity and acceleration effects.
\par

Convenient and powerful supporting utilities and tools (see
 {\uldb User's Guide}{\v UG_ABOUT} for more information on these utilities).
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Components}\par

Each of the components of the MythOS system were designed to
 be self-contained.  They rely on other components for specific
 functions, but do not utilize special knowledge beyond that
 documented for the supporting component.  This section describes
 the libraries, required supporting components, and intended uses:
\par

{\i\uldb System}{\v PG_SYSTEM_OVERVIEW}\par

The MythOS system class provides system and library controls
 for integration of the components of the MythOS collection.
 Initialization and termination of the components is provided, as
 well as environment controls and diagnostics.
\par

{\i\uldb Ivory}{\v PG_IVORY_OVERVIEW}\par

{\i Ivory} is a custom memory management system which provides
 standard memory allocation, handle-based caching, and 'arena'
 allocation to provide for the kinds of memory needed by
 entertainment software.  This library uses Win32 allocation services to
 allocate the kinds of memory needed for the memory system.  This
 library includes both a standard C-style interface and C++
 new/delete operators.
\par

{\i\uldb XFile}{\v PG_XFILE_OVERVIEW}\par

A C and C++ file system is implemented in {\i XFile} to provide
 minimal overhead block-i/o routines, as well as processing of
 complex file formats.  This library uses standard Windows file
 services to implement the file i/o operations and uses the
 new/delete operators for memory allocation to allow use with and
 without the {\i Ivory} memory manager.
\par

{\i\uldb Chronos}{\v PG_CHRONOS_OVERVIEW}\par

Real-time software requires high-resolution timer services as
 well as call-back functionality for real-time processing.
 Support for both are provided by this library.
\par

{\i\uldb Bozo}{\v PG_BOZO_OVERVIEW}\par

Multi-threading execution is a powerful technique for real-time
 applications and this library provides non-preemptive
 task-switching with a single memory image.  Support for
 semaphores and other inter-thread synchronization is provided
 for multi-tasking development.
\par

{\i\uldb Max}{\v PG_MAX_OVERVIEW}\par

Events encapsulate data into discrete packages for processing by
 applications.  {\i Max} provides an abstract event processing system
 for user-input from keyboards or other input devices.
\par

{\i\uldb Felix}{\v PG_FELIX_OVERVIEW}\par

Floating-point processing is not well supported across all
 platforms, so support for fixed-point processing is required.
 {\i Felix} provides high-performance fixed-point math operations
 including advanced functions like square-root and cosine/sine.
\par

{\i\uldb Van Gogh}{\v PG_VNGO_OVERVIEW}\par

Graphics device support is provided by the {\i Van Gogh} library for
 output of lines and images, as well as more complicated 2D
 primitives to PC video devices.  Output to virtual screens as
 well as Windows DIB and DirectDraw surfaces at various resolutions
 and color depths is included.  Extensive support for 3D is included
 for color models, shaded polygonal primitives, Z-buffering, and
 texture-mapping.  {\i XFile} is used to provide file i/o for palette
 data.
\par

{\i\uldb Escher}{\v PG_ESCH_OVERVIEW}\par

Display of 3D models and other 3D objects is performed by
 {\i Escher}, utilizing the output capabilities of {\i Van Gogh}, the math
 functions of {\i Felix}, and much of the memory-management provided
 by {\i Ivory}.  Support for triangular meshes and terrain is
 provided, along with other drawable implementations.  {\i XFile} is
 used to provide file i/o for object and model data.
\par

{\i\uldb Gutenberg}{\v PG_GBERG_OVERVIEW}\par

Text output with fonts is provided by the {\i Gutenberg} library for
 use with {\i Van Gogh} for final output.  Support for external text
 resources is also provided for easy alteration and/or
 translation of displayed strings.  {\i XFile} is used to provide
 file i/o for font and text data.
\par

{\i\uldb Turner}{\v PG_TURNER_OVERVIEW}\par

A standard interface to the network is provided by the {\i Turner}
 library which makes use of the Microsoft DirectPlay API.
\par

{\i\uldb Newton}{\v PG_NEWTON_OVERVIEW}\par

A standard Newtonian physics simulation library is provided by the
 {\i Newton} library.
\par

{\i\uldb Bach}{\v PG_BACH_OVERVIEW}\par

C++ sound library to provide a high-level inteface for the Microsoft
 DirectSound API.
\par

{\i\uldb Spielberg}{\v PG_SBERG_OVERVIEW}\par

Mulitimedia animation/movie player library with support for the Microsoft
 ActiveMovie/DirectShow API.
\par

{\i\uldb Pane}{\v PG_PANE_OVERVIEW}\par

Graphical user interface helper library with components for use with
 {\i Van Gogh} and {\i Max}.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Future Work}\par

The MythOS 95 library set represents a technology base started in 1994
 for use in Charybdis' first title.  We had plans for the development
 of a new 2.0 version of the library to provide a major rewrite of the
 graphics libraries (Van Gogh and Escher) to update for the shift
 to 3D graphics consumer hardware from software-based rendering
 on 486 class computers.  This version was to be called "MythOS 98".
\par

We are not making any commitments for a future version, but there are
 a number of plans which may or may not materialize.  Any such work
 will take place on a part-time basis and would hopefully be released
 using the same Open Source license.  The new version would be a major
 rewrite and would not be compatable with MythOS 95.
\par

