#{\footnote UG_OVERVIEW}
${\footnote Overview}
+{\footnote BW_UG_1}
{\b\f0{\cf2\scaps User's Guide}\line\fs32 Overview}\par\pard\sb100

The MythOS\'99 collection provides developers of entertainment
 and multi-media software with a wide array of useful tools which can be
 used to augment software development.
\par

This collection of tools is designed for use from the an MS-DOS Box under
 Windows 9x/NT, as a native Win32 application, or from within specific
 applications.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Audience}\par

This guide is intended for developers who have a working
 understanding of Windows 95/98/NT and the intended application of the
 MythOS software.  Some components require application specific
 knowledge.  No knowledge of C/C++/Assembly programming is
 assumed for this guide.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Features}\par

The major tools of the MythOS collection are:
\par

3D data exporter for 3D Studio\'ae Release 4 and 3D viewer for polygonal
 models and associated materials, cameras, and lights.
\par

Terrain data editor for polygonal-based terrain system.
\par

Format converters for bitmaps and other data sets.
\par

Texture librarian for manipulating exported texture data.
\par

Interactive palette generation tool for creation of high-quality shading
 palettes for application-specific needs.
\par

Data compilers for file and font systems (including TrueType font capture
 utility).
\par

Event compiler for easy redefinition of user inputs for easier product
 development and tuning.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Components}\par

Each of the components of the MythOS system require different
 utilities and tools.  This section describes the tools
 associated with each library:
\par

{\i\uldb XFile}{\v UG_XFILE_OVERVIEW}\par

The tools associated with the {\i XFile} library are for the
 creation, examination, and maintenance of data file formats. The
 Interchange File Format from Electronic Arts is used as the
 basic file format in MythOS and a compiler and directory
 utility is included for working with these files.
\par

{\i\uldb Max}{\v UG_MAX_OVERVIEW}\par

Application defined events in {\i Max} may have any number of
 associated definitions or triggers.  These are defined via a
 standard file format created by an event compiler.
\par

{\i\uldb Van Gogh}{\v UG_VNGO_OVERVIEW}\par

The quality of the color palette plays an extremely important
 role for the display of 2D primitives, particularly shaded
 primitives.  Palette conversion and creation utilities are
 included for this purpose.
\par

{\i\uldb Escher}{\v UG_ESCH_OVERVIEW}\par

3D datasets may be created in any number of applications, and
 providing a completely full-featured editor would be a
 significant investment.  {\i Escher} includes a data exporter for 3D
 Studio and other data conversion and examining utilities.
\par

{\i\uldb Gutenberg}{\v UG_GBERG_OVERVIEW}\par

Character font data and text strings are converted via tools
 supplied with {\i Gutenberg} into a format suitable for display or
 manipulation.
\par

{\i\uldb Utilities}{\v UG_UTIL_OVERVIEW}\par

Bitmap image recoloring tool for using bitmaps with specific {\i Van
 Gogh} palettes.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Future Work}\par

The collection of tools will expand as the need arises, and the
 current tools will be refined as well.  Additional components
 may require other utilities and tools.  A number of the command
 line tools will be converted to true Win32 applications for
 interactive use.
\par

